[1] Case updates
- Thu 22 Nov 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=e1cf50698c

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 21 Nov 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 393, of which 346 are confirmed and 47 are probable. In total, there were 222 deaths (175 confirmed and 47 probable) and 117 people cured.
- 73 suspected cases under investigation.
- 7 new confirmed cases, including 4 in Beni, 2 in Katwa, and 1 in Kalunguta [North Kivu].
- 3 new confirmed deaths, including 2 in Butembo and 1 in Beni.
- 4 new recoveries, including 2 in Beni and 2 in Butembo.

Continuing joint work between surveillance, laboratory, and management for the redistribution of cases and deaths by health zone as well as validation of confirmed and probable cases and deaths

News of the response
Elections 2018
--------------
- The Minister of Health, Dr Oly Ilunga Kalenga, and the President of the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC), Corneille Nangaa, had a working session this Thu 22 Nov 2018 in the Cabinet of the Minister. A joint commission between the 2 institutions was set up to coordinate their activities in the areas affected by the Ebola epidemic during the election period. The teams have already begun the work of harmonizing the maps to identify the precise location of the polling stations to be installed in the health zones affected by the epidemic. This will allow the Ministry of Health to deploy handwashing and temperature control devices at the entrance to all polling stations. "We are working together to ensure that every citizen can exercise their right to vote in all constituencies of North Kivu, including those where the disease currently occurs," said the Minister of Health.

Community engagement
--------------------
On Wed 21 Nov 2018, student representatives from several universities and higher institutions in Beni began their series of outreach sessions to youth groups hostile to the Ebola response. This awareness raising aims to educate these groups of young people about the behaviors to adopt to avoid being contaminated as well as the importance of not hampering the work of medical teams. The targets of this campaign are the young people in the 10 districts of Beni that have recorded the greatest number of resistances.

Vaccination
-----------
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 33 498 people have been vaccinated, including 16 527 in Beni.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteurs Mary Marshall and Kunihiko Iizuka

[See Helen Branswell's tweets on this DRC MoH update:
Helen Branswell @Helen Branswell https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell. - Rapp.MJM
#Ebola thread:
1. 7 more cases today and 3 deaths. They bring the outbreak totals to date to 393 confirmed and probable cases and 222 deaths. Worth noting: 117 people have survived their infections and have been discharged from care.

2. I noted recently that within a few weeks this outbreak will become the 2nd largest ever; it's on track to pass the 2000 outbreak at Gulu, Uganda, where 425 cases were recorded. At the current rate of new cases, this could happen before the end of November [2018].

3. @MinSanteRDC reports that talks are underway with the elections commission to plan for safe elections. There's a lot of concern next month's elections could amp up the in violence in North Kivu. As @WHO @DrTedros says: #Ebola shouldn't be politicized.

4. The #Ebola response continues to try to get the community in North Kivu onside with containment measures. Latest effort: Meeting with youth groups in Beni who have impeded safe burials and other containment efforts.

Earlier Branswell tweets:
1. A critical facet of controlling an #Ebola outbreak is figuring out who has been exposed and monitoring their health daily so they can be isolated asap if they start to get sick. Given the importance of this, this number -- percentage of contacts followed -- is quite worrisome.

2. I don't mean to criticize the #Ebola responders; they're working in very taxing and dangerous circumstances, dealing with people who aren't co-operating in some cases. But 89 percent means 500 people weren't followed today. This risks losing track of transmission chains.

3. @WHO leaders have said in the past that when there's violence, their ability to do follow up flags and this percentage drops, but they get it up again when things calm down. Hope this is just a vestige of last Friday's [16 Nov 2018] violence.
- Mod.LK]

- Wed 21 Nov 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=48622b0407

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 20 Nov 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 386, of which 339 are confirmed and 47 are probable. In total, there were 219 deaths (172 confirmed and 47 probable) and 113 people healed.
- 48 suspected cases under investigation.
- 13 new confirmed cases, including 7 in Katwa, 2 in Beni, 2 in Kalunguta, 1 in Oicha and 1 in Mutwanga [North Kivu].
- 2 new confirmed deaths, including 1 in Beni and 1 in Mutwanga.
- 3 new recoveries in Butembo.

News of the response
Epidemiological surveillance
---------------
- Katwa [North Kivu]: of the new cases in the Katwa health zone, 5 are family members living in the Rughenda health area. They were registered as contacts of a confirmed case of Katwa who died in early November [2018]. They had refused vaccination and follow-up. They finally agreed to be treated at Butembo ETC.

- Beni [North Kivu]: the new cases in Oicha and Mutwanga [North Kivu] are related to Beni cases. The case of Mutwanga is a known contact of a confirmed case of Beni. The case detected in Oicha came back from a stay in Beni.

- Kalunguta [North Kivu]: the situation in the Kanyihunga village, a Mai Mai-controlled area, is evolving positively. It has been 6 days since no case has been reported in this village. A total of 360 contacts were recorded in the village, of which 16 left the 21-day follow-up on Tue 20 Nov 2018, and 172 will be out of follow-up on Fri 23 Nov 2018. Other contacts will complete their follow-up period on 5 Dec 2018.

Vaccination
-----------
Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 33 077 people have been vaccinated, including 16 395 in Beni.

--
